<article title='Baseball_positions'><paragraph><link><target>Image:Baseball positions.svg</target><part>300px</part><part>right</part></link>There are 9<space/><bold>fielding positions</bold><space/>in<space/><link><target>baseball</target></link>. Each<space/><link><target>Baseball scorekeeping#Defensive positions</target><part>position</part></link><space/>conventionally has an associated number, which is used<space/><link><target>official scorer</target><part>to score</part></link><space/><link><target>putout</target><trail>s</trail></link>: 1 (<link><target>pitcher</target></link>), 2 (<link><target>catcher</target></link>), 3 (<link><target>first baseman</target></link>), 4 (<link><target>second baseman</target></link>), 5 (<link><target>third baseman</target></link>), 6 (<link><target>shortstop</target></link>), 7 (<link><target>outfielder</target><part>left fielder</part></link>), 8 (<link><target>outfielder</target><part>center fielder</part></link>), and 9 (<link><target>outfielder</target><part>right fielder</part></link>).<extension extension_name='ref'><template><target>cite book</target><arg name="first">Lyle</arg><arg name="last">Spatz</arg><arg name="title">Historical Dictionary of Baseball</arg><arg name="page">3</arg><arg name="publisher">Scarecrow Press</arg><arg name="year">2012</arg><arg name="isbn">9780810879546</arg></template></extension></paragraph><paragraph>For example:</paragraph><list type='bullet'><listitem>If the third baseman fields a ball and throws it to first, it is recorded as a 53<space/><link><target>out (baseball)</target><part>out</part></link>.</listitem><listitem>A<space/><link><target>double play</target></link><space/>where the second baseman fields, throws to the shortstop covering second base, who throws to the 1st baseman is recorded as a 463 double play.</listitem></list><heading level='2'>Other roles</heading><paragraph><template><target>Multicol</target></template></paragraph><list type='bullet'><listitem><link><targe